<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,342,871]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,497,522,547]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Description &amp; Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Wingspan 24.5– 
<quantity box="[687,768,522,546]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="28.0">28 mm</quantity>
. Similar to the smaller 
<taxonomicName box="[1028,1123,524,547]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Lithostege" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parva">
<emphasis box="[1028,1123,524,547]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L. parva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in colour, but distinguished by the darker scaling on veins crossing the very indistinct and sometimes not discernible postmedial band; also the other transverse lines weak, apical streak, as present in 
<taxonomicName box="[792,916,596,619]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Lithostege" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="griseata">
<emphasis box="[792,916,596,619]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L. griseata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[974,1104,596,619]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Lithostege" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coassata">
<emphasis box="[974,1104,596,619]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">L. coassata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, absent (
<figureCitation box="[1210,1297,594,618]" captionStart="FIGURES 27 – 31" captionStartId="33.[151,264,1953,1976]" captionTargetBox="[261,1346,248,1922]" captionTargetId="figure@33.[209,1378,193,1932]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURES 27 – 31. Adult moths of Lithostege Hübner (left column, a: upperside, right column, b: underside). 27. L. palaestinensis (Ƥ, Ahvaz, SW Iran); 28. L. luminosata (3, Kyzyl-Arvat, Turkmenia); 29. L. luigi (Ƥ, Badkhyz, Turkmenistan); 30. L. infuscata (Ƥ, Karaj, Iran); 31. L. flavicornata (3, Ak-Chehir, Turkey). Scale bar: 10 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279206/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Fig. 
<number box="[1265,1297,594,618]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="29.0">29</number>
</figureCitation>
). Frons flat, edged by a thicker wall. In male genitalia (Fig. 
<number box="[688,717,630,654]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="55.0">55</number>
) valve sclerotized only at basal half; costa short, without apical projection; harpe long, distally truncate, almost reaching dorsal margin of valve; dorsal arm widely curved, as long as valve, apically shortly spinose. Uncus narrow, pointed at apex, saccus short, rounded. Aedeagus long and narrow. Female genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[408,493,738,762]" captionStart="FIGURES 72 – 76" captionStartId="44.[151,264,1908,1931]" captionTargetBox="[282,1336,200,1887]" captionTargetId="figure@44.[243,1345,161,1887]" captionTargetPageId="44" captionText="FIGURES 72 – 76. Lithostege Hübner: Female genitalia &amp; details of abdominal integument. 72. L. palaestinensis (gen. prep. 781 H. R.; Varamin, N Iran), a: genital organ, b: 7 th tergite; 73. L. luminosata (gen. prep. J. V.; Parhai, Turkmenistan); 74. L. luigi (gen. prep. 3688 J. V; Badkhyz, Turkmenistan); 75. L. infuscata (gen. prep. 1036 H. R.; Erivan, Armenia); 76. L. flavicornata (gen. prep. 1031 H. R.; Ak-Chehir. Turkey). Scale bar: 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/279216/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
Fig. 
<number box="[461,493,738,762]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" value="74.0">74</number>
</figureCitation>
). Corpus bursae globular, almost completely spined internally, antrum narrow, elongated, sterigma not developed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,342,871]" box="[199,954,810,835]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,323,810,835]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Bionomics</emphasis>
. Specimens studied are collected in February and April.
</paragraph>
